<div class="quotetitle">Banshaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />So when the X/Y overflow, I need to change the name table.<br /></div><br />That's *exactly* it. Just keep in mind that the nametables are 240 pixels tall, so Y overflows earlier. I prefer to use vertical mirroring, so that I don't have to care about the msb of the Y coordinate (although that breaks compatibility with 4-screen games).<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />My issue is how to do it on the nes.  I don't think there is any documents about that.<br /></div><br />I guess not. Maybe taking a look at the code of some open-source game or commercial game disassemblies would help? I mentioned the Flash thing because many people who show up here do not know the basic structure of a game, and learning the hardware details of the NES is meaningless in those cases. Flash provides a quick way to experiment things, and one can get a basic game working in minutes. If you already made a few (even if very simple) game engines in the past, you probably don't need that kind of tutorial.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />I guess the more I will experiment, the more my project will shape up.<br /></div><br />I guess. IMO, games have little to do with interacting with the hardware. I usually code a few routines that take care of that part right away, and all the heavy work is actually put on the game logic. So once you're past that, you can experiment with the actual game engine and see what works best for you.<br /><br />EDIT: About the CS3 comment, well, I code in AS3 (which BTW is much better than AS2) sometimes, but I don't use Flash, I compile my code with the free Flex SDK. This means that I have *zero* debugging capabilities (not even "trace" works), but it isn't so bad, since I'm used to 6502 asm! =)<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp