<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4247&amp;p=35198#p35198"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Banshaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Hmmm... I'm not sure what you mean by that since the msb of the PPUCTRL ($2000) is the NMI set bit.<br /></div><br />Some of the <em>other</em> bits of PPUCTRL control the msb of the X and Y scroll position.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />How is it related to the scroll and why would you want to set it every time you scroll?  This is what I'm curious about right now.<br /></div><br />Because when you set PPUCTRL, you have to set <em>all eight bits</em> of PPUCTRL. When you set the msb of the X and Y scroll position, you also set the NMI enable bit, and vice versa.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Just for other people that may read this thread, the constants used in this example are:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">PPUCTRL   = $2000<br />PPUMASK   = $2001<br />PPUSCROLL = $2005<br /><br />PPUCTRL_NMI = %10000000<br /></div><br /></div><br />And I was talking about other bit fields in the register, like these:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">PPUCTRL_OBJ8X16  = %00100000<br />PPUCTRL_BG1000   = %00010000<br />PPUCTRL_OBJ1000  = %00001000<br />PPUCTRL_VRAMDOWN = %00000100<br />PPUCTRL_Y240     = %00000010<br />PPUCTRL_X256     = %00000001<br /></div><br />When you write to one, you have to write to them all. If you do this:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">lda #PPUCTRL_NMI<br />sta PPUCTRL</div><br />you are setting all the other bits to 0. This is fine for games that don't scroll and only use the first 4 KiB of CHR and 8x8 pixel sprites.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Wed Jul 23, 2008 8:34 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
